<subSubSection lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="125" pageId="29" pageNumber="124" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[828,1437,717,1092]" lastBlockId="30.[151,761,190,917]" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="125" pageId="29" pageNumber="124">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,944,717,740]" pageId="29" pageNumber="124">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Robust species, showing usually more distinct sexual dimorphism (
<figureCitation box="[1038,1127,749,772]" captionStart="Figs 138–150. 138–147" captionStartId="53.[150,187,1961,1980]" captionTargetBox="[175,1410,491,1949]" captionTargetId="figure@53.[173,1412,489,1951]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="Figs 138–150. 138–147 – Habitus: 138 – Microhoria ocreata (LaFerté-Sénectère, 1847) comb. nov.; 139 – M. oedipus (Chevrolat, 1860); 140 – M. olivacea (LaFerté-Sénectère, 1849) comb. nov.; 141 – M. paupercula (LaFerté-Sénectère, 1849) comb. nov.; 142 – M. babaulti (Pic, 1921) comb. nov.; 143 – M. cervi sp. nov.; 144 – M. sulaimanica sp. nov., paratype; 145 – M. terminata (W. L. E. Schmidt, 1842); 146 – M. anahita sp. nov.; 147 – M. angelinii (Degiovanni, 2012) comb. nov.; 148 – M. apicordiger (Bonadona, 1958) comb. nov., apex of elytra; 150 – M. gibbipennis sp. nov., apex of elytra; 150 – M. angelinii, apex of female tergum VII." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3880277" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3880277/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="124">Fig. 139</figureCitation>
), mostly with modified elytral setation (swirled setae, setose bands); rather stable in pronotal characters, with distinct and longer setose latero-basal impressions. Mesoventrite with partly bordered lateral margins (sulcus absent laterally), and well-developed longitudinal submedian carinae (
<figureCitation box="[1137,1257,909,932]" captionStart="Figs 7–14" captionStartId="6.[151,188,1998,2017]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,187,1946]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,185,1947]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 7–14. Mesothorax in ventral (left) and lateral (right) view: 7, 8 – Neocrohoria melanura (Fairmaire &amp; Germain, 1863), Chile, Malleco prov., 4 km W Victoria (DCDC); 9, 10 – Aulacoderus mutatus (Gemminger, 1870); 11, 12 – Liparoderus venator (Dufour, 1849); 13, 14 – Microhoria oedipus (Chevrolat, 1860). Scale bars: 100 μm (Figs 7–10); 200 μm (Figs 11–14)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3880225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3880225/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="124">Figs 13, 14</figureCitation>
); setose fringe of mesepimera well-developed (
<figureCitation box="[1139,1217,941,964]" captionStart="Figs 31–38. 31" captionStartId="12.[151,188,1972,1991]" captionTargetBox="[163,1427,373,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[159,1428,371,1955]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 31–38. 31 – Neocrohoria melanura (Fairmaire &amp; Germain, 1863), Chile, Malleco prov., 4 km W Victoria (DCDC), setae of metepisterna.32 – Liparoderus insignis (Lucas, 1843), antero-median margin of mesothorax. 33–36 – Mesothorax in lateral view (detail): 33 – Microhoria oedipus (Chevrolat, 1860); 34 – M. longiceps (LaFerté-Sénectère, 1849) comb. nov.; 35 – M. caeruleicolor (Pic, 1906) comb. nov.; 36 – M. gigas (Pic, 1899). comb. nov. 37, 38 – Falsophilus minutus (Pic, 1894), after KEJVAL (2015): 37 – prothorax in ventro-lateral view; 38 – intercoxal process of abdomen. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3880229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3880229/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="124">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
); submarginal setose impressions of metaventrite and abdominal sternum III conspicuous; metatibiae more or less swollen and modified in males, with two terminal spurs; male metafemora with a row of coarser setae on inner side (at least in some species); elytral apices in males conspicuously modified, subtruncate to more or less strongly excavate and lobed, with scattered secretory pores (
<figureCitation box="[490,572,254,277]" captionStart="Figs 39–46. 39, 40" captionStartId="13.[151,188,1981,2000]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,189,1892]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,186,1893]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 39–46. 39, 40 – Metacoxa: 39 – Liparoderus venator (Dufour, 1849); 40 – Microhoria oedipus (Chevrolat, 1860). 41–46 – Apex of male elytron: 41 – Microhoria fasciata (Chevrolat, 1834); 42 – M. paupercula (LaFerté-Sénectère, 1849) comb. nov.; 43 – M. oedipus (Chevrolat, 1860); 44 – M. terminata (W. L. E. Schmidt, 1842); 45 – M. caeruleicolor (Pic, 1906) comb. nov; 46 – M. heydeni (Marseul, 1879) comb. nov. Scale bars: 20 μm (Figs 41, 44–46); 50 μm (Figs 42, 43), 200 μm (Figs 39, 40)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3880231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3880231/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="125">Fig. 43</figureCitation>
). Aedeagus (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 74–77" captionStartId="29.[151,188,2034,2053]" captionTargetBox="[169,1401,1137,2024]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,1134,2031]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figs 74–77.Aedeagus:74 – Microhoria ocreata (LaFerté-Sénectère, 1847) comb. nov., lateral view; 75 – same, ventral view; 76 – M.oedipus (Chevrolat, 1860), lateral view; 77 – same, ventral view. Scale bars: 0.2 mm – A (Figs 76, 77), B (Figs 74, 75)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3880247" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3880247/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="125">Figs 76, 77</figureCitation>
): tegmen hood-like, with simple pointed apex (‘cuculliform’); gonopore free.
</paragraph>
